{"title_page": "New Body", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name          = New Body\n| type          = demo\n| released      = July 2019 (leak)\n| artist        = [[Kanye West]] featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and [[Nicki Minaj]]\n| genre         = <!--do not add unsourced genres-->\n| length        = {{Duration|m=3|s=42}}\n| writer        =\n| producer      = [[Ronny J]]\n| misc          = {{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | header      = \n | file        = New Body - Kanye West, Ty Dolla Sign, Nicki Minaj.ogg\n | description = Audio sample featuring Ty Dolla Sign's chorus and Nicki Minaj's verse.{{ffdc|New Body - Kanye West, Ty Dolla Sign, Nicki Minaj.ogg|log=2020 February 22|date=February 2020}}\n}}}}\n\n\"'''New Body'''\" is an unreleased song by American rapper [[Kanye West]], slated to be included on West's album ''Yandhi'' which was never released. The song features vocals from American singer [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and Trinidad and Tobago-born rapper [[Nicki Minaj]]. Relying on [[flute]]s being played along with a punchy bassline, the song's original lyrics are about [[body shaming]] and the stigma surrounding [[plastic surgery]]. A reworked version of the song featuring Christian-themed lyrics was later previewed at listening parties for West's ninth studio album ''[[Jesus Is King]]'' (2019). \n\nThe song was ultimately scrapped from ''Jesus Is King'' just before its October 2019 release due to creative differences between West and Minaj. Since being leaked online in July 2019, the song received positive reviews and was noted for being a highlight among other leaked ''Yandhi'' tracks. Critics praised West's reworked Christian lyrics for being more positive and respectful.\n\n==Background and recording==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = left\n| footer = Nicki Minaj (left) and Ty Dolla Sign (right) previously appeared together on Kanye West's song \"[[Violent Crimes (song)|Violent Crimes]]\" (2018).\n| image1    = Nicki Minaj Live in concert 2018 (cropped).png\n| width1    = 159\n| image2 = Ty Dolla Sign 2018 (Cropped).jpg\n| width2 = 123}}\nNicki Minaj was previously prominently featured on West's fifth studio album ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' (2010) and provided a voice memo for his eighth studio album ''[[Ye (album)|Ye]]'' (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2018/06/nicki-minaj-writing-credit-kanye-west-ye-album|title=Nicki Minaj Influenced A Lyric On Kanye West's 'Ye' Album|date=June 1, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2019|work=Vibe|author=Camille Augustin}}</ref> Ty Dolla Sign was also featured on ''Ye'', along with ''[[The Life of Pablo]]'' (2016) and ''[[Kids See Ghosts]]'' (2018), West's collaborative album with [[Kid Cudi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8459095/ty-dolla-sign-teases-kanye-west-joint-album|title=Ty Dolla $ign Teases Possibility of Joint Album With Kanye West: 'U Ready?'|date=June 4, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2019|author=Michael Saponara|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-kid-cudi-ty-dolla-sign-sued-over-kids-see-ghosts-song-report/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=March 7, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|author=Braudie Blais-Billie|title=Kanye, Kid Cudi, Ty Dolla Sign Sued Over ''Kids See Ghosts'' Song: Report}}</ref> \"New Body\" features production from American producer [[Ronny J]],<ref name=\"Xavier\">{{Cite web|url=https://xaviernewswire.com/2019/09/11/kanyes-yandhi-album-leaked-to-mixed-reviews/|title=Kanye\u2019s Yandhi album leaked to mixed reviews|date=September 11, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2019|website=[[Xavier University|The Xavier Newswire]]|author=Sebastian Augiler}}</ref> who has previously worked with West on the collaborative track \"[[I Love It (Kanye West and Lil Pump song)|I Love It]]\" with American rapper [[Lil Pump]] and later on \"[[Everything We Need]]\" featuring Ty Dolla Sign and [[Ant Clemons]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/07/ronny-j-ty-dolla-sign-rich-the-kid-lights-out|title=Ronny J Recruits Ty Dolla Sign and Rich the Kid for \"Lights Out\"|date=July 12, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|author=Joe Price}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-and-dr-dre-working-on-something-specialfor-the-fans-according-to-producer-ronny-j-news.96668.html|title=Kanye West & Dr. Dre Working On \"Something Special\" According To Producer Ronny J|date=November 27, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|author=Erika Marie}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2018, West was spotted recording music with American rapper [[6ix9ine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/tekashi-6ix9ines-controversial-career-a-timeline.html|title=The Complete History of Tekashi 6ix9ine\u2019s Controversial Career|date=September 18, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|author1=Dee Lockett|author2=Zoe Haylock}}</ref> On September 17, 2018, West announced his ninth studio album ''Yandhi'', just three months after the release of his previous solo album ''Ye'', revealing the cover art and initial release date of September 29, 2018.<ref name=\"Reveal\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/18/kanye-west-new-project-yandhi-announcement|title=Kanye West announces new project ''Yandhi''|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2019|magazine=The Fader|first=Salvator|last=Maicki|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227144745/http://www.thefader.com/2018/09/18/kanye-west-new-project-yandhi-announcement|archive-date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 27, 2018, West visited ''[[The Fader]]'' headquarters to preview new music from ''Yandhi''. Songs previewed included vocals from Ty Dolla Sign and 6ix9ine. West took out a pocket dictionary and read the definition of the word \"artificial\", explaining his view that \"a woman\u2019s pussy count goes back to zero\" after having any plastic surgery procedures done. ''The Fader'' reported that this explanation was related to the song that featured 6ix9ine.<ref name=\"FADER\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/27/kanye-west-fader-maga-hat-kaepernick|title=Here's what happened during Kanye West's visit to The Fader|website=The Fader|date=September 27, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402221719/https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/27/kanye-west-fader-maga-hat-kaepernick|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West would later feature on two tracks from 6ix9ine's debut studio album ''[[Dummy Boy]]'' (2018): \"[[Kanga (song)|Kanga]]\" and \"[[Mama (6ix9ine song)|Mama]]\", with the latter also featuring Minaj.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.49355/title.tekashi-6ix9ine-to-officially-release-dummy-boy-from-jail-today|title=Tekashi 6ix9ine Drops Official \"Dummy Boy\" Album From Jail|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=HipHopDX|author=Kyle Eustice}}</ref>\n\nWhile West was in [[New York City]] finishing up ''Yandhi'' for the season 44 premiere of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', West's wife [[Kim Kardashian]] coordinated to get Minaj featured on \"New Body\". Before recording her verse, Minaj explained that she was \"going to say some real ass shit that bitches need to hear, too, and that they want to say and be feeling like they can\u2019t say.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/kanye-west-nicki-minaj-tease-new-collaboration-new-body-on-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians|title=Kanye West & Nicki Minaj Tease New Collaboration \"New Body\" On \u2018Keeping Up With The Kardashians|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|author=Eddie Fu}}</ref><ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\">{{Cite episode|title=Kourtney's Choice|series=[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]|season=16|number=2|date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> Minaj wrote her verse within an hour after Kardashian reached out to her.<ref name=\"Verse\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-nicki-minaj-collab/|title=Kanye West & Nicki Minaj Tease \"Dope\" Collab Track \"New Body\"|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|work=[[Highsnobiety]]|author=Heather Snowden}}</ref> West failed to release ''Yandhi'' in September 2018.<ref name=\"kimreveal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477725/kanye-west-yandhi-album-pushed-back-black-friday|last=Lamarre|first=Carl|title=Kim Kardashian-West Says Kanye's 'Yandhi' Album Will Now Drop Nov. 23: 'Trust Me, It's Worth the Wait'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 1, 2018|accessdate=December 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921012651/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477725/kanye-west-yandhi-album-pushed-back-black-friday|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 1, 2019, after recording a music video for \"[[We Got Love (Teyana Taylor song)|We Got Love]]\" with [[Teyana Taylor]] in the [[TMZ]] parking lot, West confirmed he had an upcoming song on ''Yandhi'' with Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign.<ref name=\"Hot1039\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hot1039fm.com/kanye-west-reveals-nicki-minaj-and-ty-dolla-ign-will-be-on-his-next-album/|title=Kanye West reveals Nicki Minaj and Ty Dolla $ign will be on his next album|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2019|work=[[WHXT|Hot 109.3]]|publisher=[[Alpha Media]]}}</ref> On March 8, 2019, [[GOOD Music]] audio engineer Kevin Celik confirmed that the ''Yandhi'' track featuring Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign was titled \"New Body\". Celik stated that the \"record for sure is Kim K-inspired\", referring to Kardashian.<ref>{{Cite web|title='Yandhi' Engineer Says Upcoming Kanye Project Is Inspired by 'Women Empowerment'|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/yandhi-engineer-says-kanye-project-inspired-by-women-empowerment|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|author=Tara Mahadevan|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring listening parties for ''Jesus Is King'' in September 2019, West previewed a reworked version of \"New Body\".<ref name=\"NewYork\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king.html|title=Kanye West Teases 'Jesus Is King,' a New Album With No Cursing|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|first=Joe|last=Coscarelli|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001010128/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king.html|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2019, Minaj stated that she was rerecording her verse to fit the religious theme of ''Jesus Is King'', but that she and West were having disagreements.<ref name=\"JIK\"/> Minaj explained: \"What\u2019s funny is that I did a song with Kanye, that he now wants to transform into a gospel song. I done wrote three different verses chile, and I don\u2019t know. We ain\u2019t seeing eye to eye on it. I don\u2019t know, but of course, I love and respect Kanye, and Kim, we\u2019ll see what happens with that\".<ref name=\"P4k2\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-shares-official-jesus-is-king-tracklist/|title=Kanye West Shares Official ''Jesus Is King'' Tracklist|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Matthew Strauss}}</ref> \"New Body\" was previewed at a ''Jesus Is King'' listening party at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in [[Los Angeles]] two days before the album's release date, but was removed from the final track listing for the album revealed the next day.<ref name=\"P4k2\"/> The track was ultimately scrapped from the album due to the creative differences between Minaj and West.<ref name=\"P4k1\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-takeaways/|title=5 Takeaways from Kanye West\u2019s New Album, ''Jesus Is King''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|author=Sheldon Pearce}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\"New Body\" was produced by Ronny J.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> Throughout the song, [[flute]]s are played along with a punchy bassline.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> West's verse begins his verse with \"a series of quick jabs\" before switching to a more rhythmic flow.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> Minaj's verse is \"high energy\", in contrast to Ty Dolla Sign's later verse which is more \"chill\".<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> Ty Dolla Sign sings the chorus of the song.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/>\n\nThe original leaked version of \"New Body\" addressed the issues of [[slut-shaming]] and [[body shaming]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-new-body-collab-gospel-song|title=Nicki Minaj Says Kanye Wants to Turn \"New Body\" Collab Into Gospel Song: 'We Ain\u2019t Seeing Eye to Eye on It'|author=FNR Tigg|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Charles Holmes of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the song West's \"ode to the wonders of plastic surgery and the myths of [[wikt:body count|body count]]\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{Cite web|title=Kanye West\u2019s \u2018Jesus Is King\u2019 Still Sounds Like a Work-in-Progress|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-a-work-in-progress-892567/|author=Charles Holmes}}</ref> On October 1, 2018, West explained the concept of \"New Body\" in an interview with TMZ, stating:<ref name=\"JIK\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/music/2019/10/24/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-new-body.html|title=Nicki Minaj Says Kanye West Wants to Turn 'New Body' Collab Into Gospel Song|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019|work=[[BET]]|author=Alexis Reese}}</ref>\n{{quote|This concept is a 'Ye concept. I\u2019m taking two stigmas at once because I love taking stigmas and flipping them to positive. Negative energy to a positive. One of the stigmas is that men, the more people we sleep with the higher our score goes. With a woman, the more people they sleep with, people they sleep with, people consider that to be, the lower their score goes.}}\n\nHolmes described the reworked version of song previewed in September 2019 as Christian-appropriate and that the \"body is [now] simultaneously more metaphorical and metaphysical\".<ref name=\"RS\"/> Joe Coscarelli of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that the song had been \"altered for content, turning its more secular, sexual lyrics to something more chaste and respectful.\"<ref name=\"NewYork\"/> Danilo Castro of [[Heavy.com]] noted that the reworked song had no curse words and \"a more positive overall message.\"<ref name=\"Heavy\">{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-snippets-leaks/|author=Danilo Castro|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|title=LISTEN: Kanye West\u2019s 'Jesus Is King' Snippets & Leaks|work=[[Heavy.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and leak==\n[[File:Jesus is King - The Forum, LA (48951268196).jpg|thumb|right|\"New Body\" was last previewed at a ''Jesus Is King'' listening party in [[Los Angeles]] two days before the album's release.<ref name=\"P4k2\"/>]]\nWest announced that he had a song with Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign about body shaming in an October 2018 interview with TMZ.<ref name=\"Hot1039\"/> The recording of Minaj's verse was prominently showcased in an April 2019 episode of American television series ''[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]''.<ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\"/> Following the airing of the episode, Kardashian discussed the writing of the song on [[Twitter]].<ref name=\"Verse\"/> \"New Body\" was [[Internet leak|leaked online]] in July 2019 alongside another ''Yandhi'' track titled \"[[Everything We Need|The Storm]]\", featuring Ty Dolla Sign and [[XXXTentacion]].<ref name=\"LeakNewBody01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/whats-with-all-the-leaks-kanye-west-and-nicki-minaj-21-savage-young-thug-and-more-news.85403.html|title=What's With All The Leaks? Kanye West & Nicki Minaj, 21 Savage, Young Thug & More|date=July 11, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop|first=Alex|last=Zidel|accessdate=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711204104/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/whats-with-all-the-leaks-kanye-west-and-nicki-minaj-21-savage-young-thug-and-more-news.85403.html|archive-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Paul Thompson, writing for ''The Fader'', noted that the leaks didn't receive mainstream attention and were a \"minor story\" compared to West songs that had leaked previously.<ref name=\"Fader\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/yandhi-and-the-legacy-of-kanye-west-leaks|title=''Yandhi'' and the Legacy of Kanye West leaks|work=The Fader|first=Paul|last=Thompson|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824235702/https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/yandhi-and-the-legacy-of-kanye-west-leaks|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n\"New Body\" was previewed by West at multiple listening parties for ''Jesus Is King'' throughout September and October 2019.<ref name=\"NewYork\"/><ref name=\"P4k2\"/> \"New Body\" was notably absent from the listening party in [[Chicago]], but was later re-added to the track list at further parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-everything-we-know|title=Everything We Know About Kanye West\u2019s New Album \u2018Jesus Is King\u2019|author1=Jordan Rose|author2=Eric Skelton|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122171636/https://www.complex.com/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-everything-we-know/|archive-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> \"New Body\" was last previewed at the listening party at The Forum in Los Angeles two days before the album's release date, but was removed from the final track listing for the album revealed the next day.<ref name=\"P4k2\"/> The song was scrapped from the album and never released due to West and Minaj's creative differences.<ref name=\"P4k1\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nPaul Thompson, writing for ''The Fader'', compared \"New Body\" to other ''Yandhi'' leaks as being \"in various states of progress\". Thompson praised the production and polishing on Ty Dolla Sign's hook and Minaj's verse, but described West's verse as still being in demo form as he \"lapse[s] from finished lines into mumbles reference phrases\". Thompson praised \"New Body\" and the other ''Yandhi'' leaks for having \"more shape and direction that nearly anything on ''[[Ye (album)|ye]]''\" despite the unfinished lyrics.<ref name=\"Fader\"/> In writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Thompson called it \"the one song from the ''Yandhi'' leaks that sounded like it might be a hit.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-imax-forum-premiere-903335/|date=October 24, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|title=Kanye West\u2019s \u2018Jesus Is King\u2019 Events Get Grander, But the Music Still Sounds Unfinished|author=Paul Thompson|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nSam Murphy, writing for ''Cool Accidents'', described the song as becoming \"a superfan favourite\" ever since it leaked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coolaccidents.com/news/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-listening-session|date=October 1, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|title=What Went Down At Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Listening Party In New York|author=Sam Murphy|work=Cool Accidents}}</ref> Brian McCollum of the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' described the reworked version of the song previewed at listening parties as \"quickly infectious\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=Brian McCollum|title=Kanye West plays new album 'Jesus Is King' for fans in Detroit, previews new gospel movie|url=https://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/music/brian-mccollum/2019/09/27/kanye-west-plays-jesus-king-detroit-fans-previews-new-imax-movie/3794975002/|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Danilo Castro of Heavy.com described \"New Body\" as \"one of the most hotly contested tracks on ''Jesus Is King''.\"<ref name=\"Heavy\"/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Kanye West songs}}\n{{Ty Dolla Sign}}\n{{Nicki Minaj songs}}\n\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:Body image in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Unreleased songs]]\n[[Category:Kanye West songs]]\n[[Category:Ty Dolla Sign songs]]\n[[Category:Nicki Minaj songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ronny J]]\n[[Category:Works about plastic surgery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name          = New Body\n| type          = demo\n| released      = July 2019 (leak)\n| artist        = [[Kanye West]] featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and [[Nicki Minaj]]\n| genre         = <!--do not add unsourced genres-->\n| length        = {{Duration|m=3|s=42}}\n| writer        =\n| producer      = [[Ronny J]]\n| misc          = {{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | header      = \n | file        = New Body - Kanye West, Ty Dolla Sign, Nicki Minaj.ogg\n | description = Audio sample featuring Ty Dolla Sign's chorus and Nicki Minaj's verse.{{ffdc|New Body - Kanye West, Ty Dolla Sign, Nicki Minaj.ogg|log=2020 February 22|date=February 2020}}\n}}}}\n\n\"'''New Body'''\" is an unreleased song by American rapper [[Kanye West]], slated to be included on West's album ''Yandhi'' which was never released. The song features vocals from American singer [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and Trinidad and Tobago-born rapper [[Nicki Minaj]]. Relying on [[flute]]s being played along with a punchy bassline, the song's original lyrics are about [[body shaming]] and the stigma surrounding [[plastic surgery]]. A reworked version of the song featuring Christian-themed lyrics was later previewed at listening parties for West's ninth studio album ''[[Jesus Is King]]'' (2019). \n\nThe song was ultimately scrapped from ''Jesus Is King'' just before its October 2019 release due to creative differences between West and Minaj. Since being leaked online in July 2019, the song received positive reviews and was noted for being a highlight among other leaked ''Yandhi'' tracks. Critics praised West's reworked Christian lyrics for being more positive and respectful.\n\n==Background and recording==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = left\n| footer = Nicki Minaj (left) and Ty Dolla Sign (right) previously appeared together on Kanye West's song \"[[Violent Crimes (song)|Violent Crimes]]\" (2018).\n| image1    = Nicki Minaj Live in concert 2018.png\n| width1    = 135\n| image2 = Ty Dolla Sign 2018 (Cropped).jpg\n| width2 = 125}}\nNicki Minaj was previously prominently featured on West's fifth studio album ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' (2010) and provided a voice memo for his eighth studio album ''[[Ye (album)|Ye]]'' (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2018/06/nicki-minaj-writing-credit-kanye-west-ye-album|title=Nicki Minaj Influenced A Lyric On Kanye West's 'Ye' Album|date=June 1, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2019|work=Vibe|author=Camille Augustin}}</ref> Ty Dolla Sign was also featured on ''Ye'', along with ''[[The Life of Pablo]]'' (2016) and ''[[Kids See Ghosts]]'' (2018), West's collaborative album with [[Kid Cudi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8459095/ty-dolla-sign-teases-kanye-west-joint-album|title=Ty Dolla $ign Teases Possibility of Joint Album With Kanye West: 'U Ready?'|date=June 4, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2019|author=Michael Saponara|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-kid-cudi-ty-dolla-sign-sued-over-kids-see-ghosts-song-report/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=March 7, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|author=Braudie Blais-Billie|title=Kanye, Kid Cudi, Ty Dolla Sign Sued Over ''Kids See Ghosts'' Song: Report}}</ref> \"New Body\" features production from American producer [[Ronny J]],<ref name=\"Xavier\">{{Cite web|url=https://xaviernewswire.com/2019/09/11/kanyes-yandhi-album-leaked-to-mixed-reviews/|title=Kanye\u2019s Yandhi album leaked to mixed reviews|date=September 11, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2019|website=[[Xavier University|The Xavier Newswire]]|author=Sebastian Augiler}}</ref> who has previously worked with West on the collaborative track \"[[I Love It (Kanye West and Lil Pump song)|I Love It]]\" with American rapper [[Lil Pump]] and later on \"[[Everything We Need]]\" featuring Ty Dolla Sign and [[Ant Clemons]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/07/ronny-j-ty-dolla-sign-rich-the-kid-lights-out|title=Ronny J Recruits Ty Dolla Sign and Rich the Kid for \"Lights Out\"|date=July 12, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|author=Joe Price}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kanye-west-and-dr-dre-working-on-something-specialfor-the-fans-according-to-producer-ronny-j-news.96668.html|title=Kanye West & Dr. Dre Working On \"Something Special\" According To Producer Ronny J|date=November 27, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020|website=HotNewHipHop|author=Erika Marie}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2018, West was spotted recording music with American rapper [[6ix9ine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/tekashi-6ix9ines-controversial-career-a-timeline.html|title=The Complete History of Tekashi 6ix9ine\u2019s Controversial Career|date=September 18, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|author1=Dee Lockett|author2=Zoe Haylock}}</ref> On September 17, 2018, West announced his ninth studio album ''Yandhi'', just three months after the release of his previous solo album ''Ye'', revealing the cover art and initial release date of September 29, 2018.<ref name=\"Reveal\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/18/kanye-west-new-project-yandhi-announcement|title=Kanye West announces new project ''Yandhi''|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2019|magazine=The Fader|first=Salvator|last=Maicki|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227144745/http://www.thefader.com/2018/09/18/kanye-west-new-project-yandhi-announcement|archive-date=February 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 27, 2018, West visited ''[[The Fader]]'' headquarters to preview new music from ''Yandhi''. Songs previewed included vocals from Ty Dolla Sign and 6ix9ine. West took out a pocket dictionary and read the definition of the word \"artificial\", explaining his view that \"a woman\u2019s pussy count goes back to zero\" after having any plastic surgery procedures done. ''The Fader'' reported that this explanation was related to the song that featured 6ix9ine.<ref name=\"FADER\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/27/kanye-west-fader-maga-hat-kaepernick|title=Here's what happened during Kanye West's visit to The Fader|website=The Fader|date=September 27, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402221719/https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/27/kanye-west-fader-maga-hat-kaepernick|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West would later feature on two tracks from 6ix9ine's debut studio album ''[[Dummy Boy]]'' (2018): \"[[Kanga (song)|Kanga]]\" and \"[[Mama (6ix9ine song)|Mama]]\", with the latter also featuring Minaj.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.49355/title.tekashi-6ix9ine-to-officially-release-dummy-boy-from-jail-today|title=Tekashi 6ix9ine Drops Official \"Dummy Boy\" Album From Jail|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=HipHopDX|author=Kyle Eustice}}</ref>\n\nWhile West was in [[New York City]] finishing up ''Yandhi'' for the season 44 premiere of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', West's wife [[Kim Kardashian]] coordinated to get Minaj featured on \"New Body\". Before recording her verse, Minaj explained that she was \"going to say some real ass shit that bitches need to hear, too, and that they want to say and be feeling like they can\u2019t say.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/kanye-west-nicki-minaj-tease-new-collaboration-new-body-on-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians|title=Kanye West & Nicki Minaj Tease New Collaboration \"New Body\" On \u2018Keeping Up With The Kardashians|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|author=Eddie Fu}}</ref><ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\">{{Cite episode|title=Kourtney's Choice|series=[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]|season=16|number=2|date=April 7, 2019}}</ref> Minaj wrote her verse within an hour after Kardashian reached out to her.<ref name=\"Verse\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/kanye-west-nicki-minaj-collab/|title=Kanye West & Nicki Minaj Tease \"Dope\" Collab Track \"New Body\"|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|work=[[Highsnobiety]]|author=Heather Snowden}}</ref> West failed to release ''Yandhi'' in September 2018.<ref name=\"kimreveal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477725/kanye-west-yandhi-album-pushed-back-black-friday|last=Lamarre|first=Carl|title=Kim Kardashian-West Says Kanye's 'Yandhi' Album Will Now Drop Nov. 23: 'Trust Me, It's Worth the Wait'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 1, 2018|accessdate=December 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921012651/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8477725/kanye-west-yandhi-album-pushed-back-black-friday|archive-date=September 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 1, 2019, after recording a music video for \"[[We Got Love (Teyana Taylor song)|We Got Love]]\" with [[Teyana Taylor]] in the [[TMZ]] parking lot, West confirmed he had an upcoming song on ''Yandhi'' with Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign.<ref name=\"Hot1039\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hot1039fm.com/kanye-west-reveals-nicki-minaj-and-ty-dolla-ign-will-be-on-his-next-album/|title=Kanye West reveals Nicki Minaj and Ty Dolla $ign will be on his next album|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2019|work=[[WHXT|Hot 109.3]]|publisher=[[Alpha Media]]}}</ref> On March 8, 2019, [[GOOD Music]] audio engineer Kevin Celik confirmed that the ''Yandhi'' track featuring Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign was titled \"New Body\". Celik stated that the \"record for sure is Kim K-inspired\", referring to Kardashian.<ref>{{Cite web|title='Yandhi' Engineer Says Upcoming Kanye Project Is Inspired by 'Women Empowerment'|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/03/yandhi-engineer-says-kanye-project-inspired-by-women-empowerment|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|author=Tara Mahadevan|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring listening parties for ''Jesus Is King'' in September 2019, West previewed a reworked version of \"New Body\".<ref name=\"NewYork\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king.html|title=Kanye West Teases 'Jesus Is King,' a New Album With No Cursing|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|first=Joe|last=Coscarelli|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001010128/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/arts/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king.html|archive-date=October 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2019, Minaj stated that she was rerecording her verse to fit the religious theme of ''Jesus Is King'', but that she and West were having disagreements.<ref name=\"JIK\"/> Minaj explained: \"What\u2019s funny is that I did a song with Kanye, that he now wants to transform into a gospel song. I done wrote three different verses chile, and I don\u2019t know. We ain\u2019t seeing eye to eye on it. I don\u2019t know, but of course, I love and respect Kanye, and Kim, we\u2019ll see what happens with that\".<ref name=\"P4k2\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kanye-west-shares-official-jesus-is-king-tracklist/|title=Kanye West Shares Official ''Jesus Is King'' Tracklist|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=16 December 2019|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Matthew Strauss}}</ref> \"New Body\" was previewed at a ''Jesus Is King'' listening party at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in [[Los Angeles]] two days before the album's release date, but was removed from the final track listing for the album revealed the next day.<ref name=\"P4k2\"/> The track was ultimately scrapped from the album due to the creative differences between Minaj and West.<ref name=\"P4k1\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-takeaways/|title=5 Takeaways from Kanye West\u2019s New Album, ''Jesus Is King''|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|author=Sheldon Pearce}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n\"New Body\" was produced by Ronny J.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> Throughout the song, [[flute]]s are played along with a punchy bassline.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> West's verse begins his verse with \"a series of quick jabs\" before switching to a more rhythmic flow.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> Minaj's verse is \"high energy\", in contrast to Ty Dolla Sign's later verse which is more \"chill\".<ref name=\"Xavier\"/> Ty Dolla Sign sings the chorus of the song.<ref name=\"Xavier\"/>\n\nThe original leaked version of \"New Body\" addressed the issues of [[slut-shaming]] and [[body shaming]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/10/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-new-body-collab-gospel-song|title=Nicki Minaj Says Kanye Wants to Turn \"New Body\" Collab Into Gospel Song: 'We Ain\u2019t Seeing Eye to Eye on It'|author=FNR Tigg|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Charles Holmes of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the song West's \"ode to the wonders of plastic surgery and the myths of [[wikt:body count|body count]]\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{Cite web|title=Kanye West\u2019s \u2018Jesus Is King\u2019 Still Sounds Like a Work-in-Progress|date=September 30, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-wests-jesus-is-king-a-work-in-progress-892567/|author=Charles Holmes}}</ref> On October 1, 2018, West explained the concept of \"New Body\" in an interview with TMZ, stating:<ref name=\"JIK\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/music/2019/10/24/nicki-minaj-kanye-west-new-body.html|title=Nicki Minaj Says Kanye West Wants to Turn 'New Body' Collab Into Gospel Song|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=14 December 2019|work=[[BET]]|author=Alexis Reese}}</ref>\n{{quote|This concept is a 'Ye concept. I\u2019m taking two stigmas at once because I love taking stigmas and flipping them to positive. Negative energy to a positive. One of the stigmas is that men, the more people we sleep with the higher our score goes. With a woman, the more people they sleep with, people they sleep with, people consider that to be, the lower their score goes.}}\n\nHolmes described the reworked version of song previewed in September 2019 as Christian-appropriate and that the \"body is [now] simultaneously more metaphorical and metaphysical\".<ref name=\"RS\"/> Joe Coscarelli of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that the song had been \"altered for content, turning its more secular, sexual lyrics to something more chaste and respectful.\"<ref name=\"NewYork\"/> Danilo Castro of [[Heavy.com]] noted that the reworked song had no curse words and \"a more positive overall message.\"<ref name=\"Heavy\">{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/10/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-snippets-leaks/|author=Danilo Castro|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|title=LISTEN: Kanye West\u2019s 'Jesus Is King' Snippets & Leaks|work=[[Heavy.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and leak==\n[[File:Jesus is King - The Forum, LA (48951268196).jpg|thumb|right|\"New Body\" was last previewed at a ''Jesus Is King'' listening party in [[Los Angeles]] two days before the album's release.<ref name=\"P4k2\"/>]]\nWest announced that he had a song with Minaj and Ty Dolla Sign about body shaming in an October 2018 interview with TMZ.<ref name=\"Hot1039\"/> The recording of Minaj's verse was prominently showcased in an April 2019 episode of American television series ''[[Keeping Up with the Kardashians]]''.<ref name=\"KUWTKs16e2\"/> Following the airing of the episode, Kardashian discussed the writing of the song on [[Twitter]].<ref name=\"Verse\"/> \"New Body\" was [[Internet leak|leaked online]] in July 2019 alongside another ''Yandhi'' track titled \"[[Everything We Need|The Storm]]\", featuring Ty Dolla Sign and [[XXXTentacion]].<ref name=\"LeakNewBody01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/whats-with-all-the-leaks-kanye-west-and-nicki-minaj-21-savage-young-thug-and-more-news.85403.html|title=What's With All The Leaks? Kanye West & Nicki Minaj, 21 Savage, Young Thug & More|date=July 11, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop|first=Alex|last=Zidel|accessdate=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711204104/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/whats-with-all-the-leaks-kanye-west-and-nicki-minaj-21-savage-young-thug-and-more-news.85403.html|archive-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Paul Thompson, writing for ''The Fader'', noted that the leaks didn't receive mainstream attention and were a \"minor story\" compared to West songs that had leaked previously.<ref name=\"Fader\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/yandhi-and-the-legacy-of-kanye-west-leaks|title=''Yandhi'' and the Legacy of Kanye West leaks|work=The Fader|first=Paul|last=Thompson|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824235702/https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/23/yandhi-and-the-legacy-of-kanye-west-leaks|archive-date=August 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n\"New Body\" was previewed by West at multiple listening parties for ''Jesus Is King'' throughout September and October 2019.<ref name=\"NewYork\"/><ref name=\"P4k2\"/> \"New Body\" was notably absent from the listening party in [[Chicago]], but was later re-added to the track list at further parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-everything-we-know|title=Everything We Know About Kanye West\u2019s New Album \u2018Jesus Is King\u2019|author1=Jordan Rose|author2=Eric Skelton|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122171636/https://www.complex.com/music/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-album-everything-we-know/|archive-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> \"New Body\" was last previewed at the listening party at The Forum in Los Angeles two days before the album's release date, but was removed from the final track listing for the album revealed the next day.<ref name=\"P4k2\"/> The song was scrapped from the album and never released due to West and Minaj's creative differences.<ref name=\"P4k1\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nPaul Thompson, writing for ''The Fader'', compared \"New Body\" to other ''Yandhi'' leaks as being \"in various states of progress\". Thompson praised the production and polishing on Ty Dolla Sign's hook and Minaj's verse, but described West's verse as still being in demo form as he \"lapse[s] from finished lines into mumbles reference phrases\". Thompson praised \"New Body\" and the other ''Yandhi'' leaks for having \"more shape and direction that nearly anything on ''[[Ye (album)|ye]]''\" despite the unfinished lyrics.<ref name=\"Fader\"/> In writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Thompson called it \"the one song from the ''Yandhi'' leaks that sounded like it might be a hit.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-imax-forum-premiere-903335/|date=October 24, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019|title=Kanye West\u2019s \u2018Jesus Is King\u2019 Events Get Grander, But the Music Still Sounds Unfinished|author=Paul Thompson|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nSam Murphy, writing for ''Cool Accidents'', described the song as becoming \"a superfan favourite\" ever since it leaked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coolaccidents.com/news/kanye-west-jesus-is-king-listening-session|date=October 1, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019|title=What Went Down At Kanye West's 'Jesus Is King' Listening Party In New York|author=Sam Murphy|work=Cool Accidents}}</ref> Brian McCollum of the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' described the reworked version of the song previewed at listening parties as \"quickly infectious\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=Brian McCollum|title=Kanye West plays new album 'Jesus Is King' for fans in Detroit, previews new gospel movie|url=https://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/music/brian-mccollum/2019/09/27/kanye-west-plays-jesus-king-detroit-fans-previews-new-imax-movie/3794975002/|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Danilo Castro of Heavy.com described \"New Body\" as \"one of the most hotly contested tracks on ''Jesus Is King''.\"<ref name=\"Heavy\"/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Kanye West songs}}\n{{Ty Dolla Sign}}\n{{Nicki Minaj songs}}\n\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:Body image in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Unreleased songs]]\n[[Category:Kanye West songs]]\n[[Category:Ty Dolla Sign songs]]\n[[Category:Nicki Minaj songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ronny J]]\n[[Category:Works about plastic surgery]]\n", "name_user": "Nice4What", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground and recording:Cropped Minaj photo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Body"}
{"title_page": "Jonathan King", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Jonathan King\n|image         = Jonathan_King_in_2007_cr.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|alt           = photograph\n|caption       = King in 2007\n|birth_name    = Kenneth George King\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1944|12|6|df=y}}<ref name=walker />\n|birth_place   = [[London]], England\n|known_for     = [[Pop music]], discovery of [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], early [[10cc]] and [[Bay City Rollers]] hits\n|television    = ''[[Entertainment USA]]'' (BBC)\n|education     = [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]]\n|alma_mater    =  [[Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n|occupation    = Record producer, singer-songwriter, music entrepreneur, TV presenter\n|notable works = \"[[Everyone's Gone to the Moon]]\" (1965) and other singles\n|awards        = Music Industry Trusts Award, 1997<ref name=MITAward/>\n|website       = [http://www.kingofhits.com/ www.kingofhits.com]\n}}\n'''Jonathan King''' (born '''Kenneth George King''', 6 December 1944) is an English [[singer-songwriter]], [[record producer]], music entrepreneur, and former television and radio presenter.\n\nKing first came to prominence in 1965 when \"[[Everyone's Gone to the Moon]]\", a song that he wrote and sang while still an [[undergraduate]], achieved chart success.<ref name=Eder/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported in 2002 that he had sold over 40 million records in his career.<ref name=\"ronson_fall\" />  As an independent producer, he discovered and named [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] in 1967, producing their first album ''[[From Genesis to Revelation]]''. He founded his own label, [[UK Records]] in 1972. He released and produced songs for [[10cc]] and the [[Bay City Rollers]]. In the 1970s King became known for hits that he performed and/or produced under different names, including \"[[Johnny Reggae]]\", \"[[Loop di Love]]\", \"[[Sugar Sugar]]\", \"[[It Only Takes A Minute]]\", \"[[Hooked On A Feeling]]\" and \"[[Paloma Blanca|Una Paloma Blanca]]\"; between September 1971 and 1972 alone he produced 10 [[UK Singles Chart|top 30 singles]] in the UK.<ref name=BillboardSept1972>\"King Forms U.K. Records,\" ''Billboard'', 9 September 1972, [https://books.google.com/books?id=4icEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32 32].</ref> [[Rod Liddle]] described him as someone who could \"storm the pop charts at will, under a hundred different disguises\".<ref>Liddle, Rod (11 April 2010). [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/rod_liddle/article7094203.ece \"McLaren was no cultural genius just a lucky punk\"], ''The Sunday Times''. London.</ref>\n\nWhile living in New York in the 1980s, King appeared on radio and television in the UK, including on the BBC's ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' and ''[[Entertainment USA]]''. In the early 1990s he produced the [[Brit Awards]], and from 1995 he selected and produced the British entries for the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], including the winning entry in 1997, \"[[Love Shine a Light]]\" by [[Katrina and the Waves]].<ref name=BBC24Nov2000/>\n\nIn September 2001, King was convicted of [[Child sexual abuse in the United Kingdom|child sexual abuse]] and sentenced to seven years in prison, for having sexually assaulted five boys, aged 14 and 15, in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/nov/21/childprotection.society |title=Jonathan King jailed for child sex abuse |date=21 November 2001 |work=The Guardian |location= London}}</ref> In November 2001 he was acquitted of 22 similar charges.<ref name=apology /> He was released on parole in March 2005.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/4388913.stm \"Jonathan King freed from prison\"], BBC News, 29 March 2005.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3567549/Is-proof-Jonathan-King-DIDN-T-abuse-teenage-boys-New-evidence-suggests-pop-mogul-alibi-sent-jail.html |title=Is this proof that Jonathan King DIDN'T abuse teenage boys?|work= Mail on Sunday |location= London |date=30 April 2016 |authorlink=Bob Woffinden |last=Woffinden |first=Bob}}</ref> A further trial for sexual offences against teenage boys resulted in several not guilty verdicts and the trial being abandoned in June 2018.<ref name = \"2018_trial\" /><ref name= \"finkelstein\">{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Finkelstein |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/trials-of-jonathan-king-should-worry-us-all-795ct8f79 |title=Trials of Jonathan King should worry us all |newspaper=The Times |location= London |date=15 August 2018 |accessdate=25 August 2018}}{{subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\n===Family background===\n[[File:Brookhurst Grange, Ewhurst, Surrey (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=1.20|Brookhurst Grange, [[Ewhurst, Surrey|Ewhurst]]]]\nKing was born in a nursing home in Bentinck Street, [[Marylebone]], London, the first child of Jimmy King  (d. 1954) and his wife, Ailsa Linley Leon (1916\u20132007), a former actress.<ref>[http://www.kingofhits.co.uk/component/option,com_gallery2/Itemid,64/?g2_itemId=472 \"Ailsa Linley\"], www.kingofhits.co.uk; King, Jonathan (2009). ''65 My Life So Far'', London: Revvolution Publishing Ltd., chs.&nbsp;1, 25.</ref> Originally from New Jersey, Jimmy King had moved to England when he was 14. He attended [[Oundle School]] and Trinity College, Cambridge, before joining the [[American Field Service]] during World War II and later [[Tootal]] Ties and Shirts as managing director.<ref name=King2/>\n\nKing's birth was a [[Forceps in childbirth|forceps delivery]] and a muscle on his upper lip was affected during it, giving him his slightly crooked smile.<ref name=King1>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;1.</ref><ref name=Chalmers22April2012/> After he was born, the family lived in Gloucester Place, Marylebone, then moved to Surrey, where King and his younger brothers, James and Anthony (\"Andy\"), were raised in Brookhurst Grange, a mansion near [[Ewhurst, Surrey|Ewhurst]].<ref name=King1/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.kingofhits.co.uk/index.php?option=com_gallery2&Itemid=64&g2_itemId=899 |title=Brookhurst Grange Ewhurst Surrey| publisher = kingofhits.co.uk |author=King, Jonathan |accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Stoke House and Charterhouse===\nKing was sent to [[boarding school]], first as a weekly boarder to pre-prep school in [[Hindhead]], Surrey, then, when he was eight, to Stoke House Preparatory School in [[Seaford, East Sussex]].<ref name=King2>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;2.</ref> A year later, in 1954, after his father died from a heart attack, Brookhurst Grange was sold and the family moved to Cobbetts, a cottage in nearby [[Abinger|Forest Green]].<ref name=King3>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;3.</ref>\n\nMusic became his passion around this time. King would save his pocket money for train trips to London to watch ''[[My Fair Lady]]'', ''[[The King and I]]'', ''[[Irma La Douce (musical)|Irma la Douce]]'', ''[[Salad Days (musical)|Salad Days]]'', ''[[Damn Yankees]]'' and ''[[Kismet (musical)|Kismet]]'' from the cheap seats in the balcony. He also discovered [[pop music]] and bought his first single, [[Guy Mitchell]]'s \"[[Singing the Blues]]\" (1956).<ref name=King3/><ref name=King4>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;4.</ref>\n\nIn 1958 King became a boarder at [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]] in [[Godalming]], Surrey. He wrote that he \"loved Charterhouse immediately\", with its history and \"every possible area of encouragement from sport to intellectual pursuits.\" Unlike at Stoke House, there were other boys there who appreciated pop music. He bought a [[transistor radio]] and earphones and joined the \"under the bedclothes\" club, listening to [[Tony Hall (music executive)|Tony Hall]], [[Jimmy Savile]], Don Moss and [[Pete Murray (DJ)|Pete Murray]] on [[Radio Luxembourg]], and keeping track of the ''[[New Musical Express]]'' charts.<ref name=King4/> The music, particularly [[Buddy Holly]], [[Adam Faith]], [[Roy Orbison]] and [[Gene Pitney]], made him \"ache with desire\":\n\n<blockquote style=\"background:none; margin-right:5em; margin-left:0; border-left:solid 3px #ccc; padding:1.5em;\">\nSince \"[[It Doesn't Matter Anymore]]\" swept me off my feet, I had become a raving pop addict, desperate for a fix every few seconds. I kept thick notebooks packed with copies of the weekly charts, adverts for new products, pages of predictions of future hits, reviews and comments about current artistes. Looking at them now, there was no way I could ever have avoided a future in the music industry.<ref name=King4/></blockquote>\n\n===Gap year===\nKing left Charterhouse in 1962 to attend Davies's, a London [[Cram school|crammer]], for his [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|A level]]s. With his wages from a job stacking shelves in a supermarket, he made a demo of himself the following year singing \"[[It Doesn't Matter Anymore]]\" and \"Fool's Paradise\" [[Shane Fenton|Eden Kane song]] with the Ted Taylor Trio, a professional group in [[Rickmansworth]].<ref name=King6/> Wearing a pinstripe suit and trainers, he approached [[John Schroeder (musician)|John Schroeder]] of [[Oriole Records (UK)|Oriole Records]] and told him he could make a hit record. \"I have been studying the music industry for the last three years and it is one big joke,\" Schroeder reported him as saying. \"Anyone can make it if they're clever and can fool a few people.\" After hearing King's demo, Schroeder booked a studio session with an orchestra but suspected that King could not sing in tune.<ref>Schroeder, John (2016). ''All for the Love of Music'', Matador, 66\u201368.</ref>\n\nKing also joined a local band in [[Cranleigh]], the Bumblies, as manager/producer and occasional singer, sometimes wearing thigh-length boots and long black gloves, during the band's appearances at birthday parties and similar.<ref name=King6>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;6.</ref>\n\nDespite the cramming, King failed the scholarship exam for [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], but he was offered a place in 1963 after an interview.<ref name=King6/> He accepted, but first took a [[gap year]] and spent six months travelling with a [[round-the-world ticket]] from his mother. Staying mostly in youth hostels, he visited Greece, the Middle East, Asia, Australia and the United States, including Hawaii, where, in June 1964, he met the manager of the [[The Beatles|Beatles]], [[Brian Epstein]]. They spent hours together in Honolulu discussing the music industry, King wrote.<ref name=King7>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;7.</ref><ref name=PA29March2005>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/mar/29/ukcrime.childprotection1 |title=The rise and fall of a pop tsar |agency=Press Association |date=29 March 2005}}</ref>{{efn|For June 1964: King flew to Hawaii a week after booking himself into the [[Southern Cross Hotel]] in Melbourne, where the Beatles were staying. The Beatles were there for four days from 14 June 1964.<ref>Cahill, Mikey (18 June 2014). [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/photo-essay-a-look-back-at-how-the-beatles-rocked-melbourne-and-their-teenage-fans-went-wild/story-fnkd6ppg-1226957342975 \"Photo essay: A look back at how the Beatles rocked Melbourne and their teenage fans went wild\"], ''Herald Sun''.</ref>}} In October that year King began to study for his degree in English literature at Cambridge, lodging in [[Jesus Lane]].<ref name=King8/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early success===\n{{further|1960s in music}}\n[[File:Jonathan King Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|left|In London, 1969 (photograph by [[Allan Warren]])]]\n{{Listen\n |filename     = Everyone's Gone To The Moon - Jonathan King.ogg\n |title        = Jonathan King \u2013 \"Everyone's Gone to the Moon\" (1965)\n |description  = \"Everyone's Gone to the Moon\" was written and performed by King while he was at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]]}}\nAround the time King began at Cambridge, the Bumblies (featuring Terry Ward) recorded a song he had written and produced, \"Gotta Tell\", which King persuaded [[Fontana Records]] to release. It appeared in April 1965 and \"rightly sank without trace\", King writes, but the experience of taking it from label to label, and then trying to find people to play it, taught him how to promote a record. He called DJs and television producers to ask them to listen to it and, because it was Easter, delivered hundreds of vinyl singles to music critics complete with Easter eggs he had painted himself.<ref name=\"King6\"/> King and the Bumblies recorded another of his songs, \"All You've Gotta Do\", with producer [[Joe Meek]], but nothing came of it.<ref name=King7/><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KY1UGtXFRIE&t=8m0s \"The Joe Meek Story\"], 8 February 1991, 00:08:02.</ref>\n\nKeen to break into the music business, King contacted [[Tony Hall (music executive)|Tony Hall]] of [[Decca Records]], who put him in touch with the [[Zombies]]' producers Ken Jones and Joe Roncoroni. King played them one of his songs, \"Green is the Grass\", and they asked him to write a [[A-side and B-side|B side]]. He offered them six songs, including \"[[Everyone's Gone to the Moon]]\", which became the A side. They also suggested he change his name.<ref name=King8>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;8.</ref>\n\nDecca released \"[[Everyone's Gone to the Moon]]\" in August 1965.<ref name=Lazell/> Relying on the contacts he had made while promoting \"Gotta Tell\", King plugged it relentlessly to radio stations to get it on their playlists. DJ Tony Windsor of [[Wonderful Radio London|Radio London]], a [[Pirate radio in the United Kingdom|pirate station]] broadcast from the ''[[USS Density (AM-218)|MV Galaxy]]'', was the first to play it, not only once, but three times in a row. (Windsor later said he did this only because of a problem with his other turntable.) It sold 26,000 copies the next day.<ref>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;9.</ref>\n\nWhen the song made number 18 in the charts, King was invited onto the BBC's ''[[Top of the Pops]]'', introduced by Jimmy Savile. The following day it sold 35,000 copies.<ref>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;9; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=traW5spkJs8 \"Everyone's Gone to the Moon\"], ''Top of the Pops'', BBC, 1965.</ref> It peaked at number four in the UK (the Beatles were at number one with \"[[Help! (song)|Help!]]\") and 17 in the US, and was awarded a [[music recording sales certification|gold disc]].<ref name=Lazell>Lazell, Barry (1989). ''Rock movers & shakers'', Billboard Publications, 279.</ref><ref>For number three, ''Melody Maker'', 21 August 1965, cited in King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;9.</ref><ref name=\"The Book of Golden Discs\">{{cite book| first= Joseph| last= Murrells| year= 1978| title= The Book of Golden Discs| edition= 2nd| publisher= Barrie and Jenkins Ltd| location= London| at= [https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/192 192]| isbn= 978-0-214-20512-5| url-access= registration| url= https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/192}}</ref><ref>Warwick, Neil; Kutner, Jon; and Brown, Tony (2004). ''The Complete Book of the British charts: Singles & Albums''. Omnibus Press, 602.</ref><ref>Nite, Norm N. (1978). ''Rock on. The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Rock N' Roll: The Solid Gold Years''. Ty Crowell Co, 262.</ref> [[Nina Simone]], [[Bette Midler]], and [[Marlene Dietrich]] all covered it. Dietrich sang \"Everyone's Gone to the Moon\" and its B side, \"Summer's Coming\", at the [[Golders Green Hippodrome]] in October 1966, with an arrangement by [[Burt Bacharach]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG4QkIkTDIA \"Marlene Dietrich sings \"Everyone's Gone to the Moon\" (Live, 1966)\"], YouTube.</ref><ref name=walker>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Tim |title= Jonathan King: 'My book's an online hit, millions click on my videos. How about lifting the media ban on me?' |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jonathan-king-my-books-an-online--hit-millions-click-on-my-videos-how-about-lifting-the-media-ban-on-me-6268884.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=28 November 2011}}</ref> The single reached No. 17 in the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{citation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NDUGbT9d4hcC |page=43 |title=99 Red Balloons...and 100 Other All-Time Great One-Hit Wonders |author=Brent Mann|work=Books.google.co.uk|accessdate=2015-11-28|isbn=9780806525167 |year=2003 }}</ref><ref name=\"gdn220050329\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/mar/29/ukcrime.childprotection1 |title=The rise and fall of a pop tsar |agency=Press Association |date=29 March 2005 |newspaper=The Guardian |location =London}}</ref> and was one of the songs carried on the [[Apollo 11]] moon mission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2019/07/03/journey-moon-master-theremin/ecu7OqQx8FYBt230BtJdNJ/story.html|title=A journey to the moon, by a master of the theremin - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref> In 2019, the track was included in the soundtrack of the Hollywood film ''[[In the Shadow of the Moon (2019 film)|In The Shadow Of The Moon]]'' over the closing credits.<ref>https://www.tunefind.com/movie/in-the-shadow-of-the-moon-2019 In the Shadow of the Moon Soundtrack]</ref>.\n\nFrom his second year at university, King split his time between Cambridge and London, moving into a three-bedroom apartment, owned by his mother, at 20 St Andrews Mansions, [[Dorset Street, London|Dorset Street]], [[Marylebone]], driving there from classes in his white [[MGB GT]].<ref>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', chs.&nbsp;2, 9.</ref> His next release, \"Green is the Grass\", flopped, but the third (which he wrote and produced, but did not perform), \"[[It's Good News Week]]\" by [[Hedgehoppers Anonymous]], was a hit. It was released in September 1965 through Decca and credited to King and his new publishing company, JonJo Music Co. Ltd, which was named after King, Ken Jones and Joe Roncoroni and based in Jones' and Roncoroni's office at 37 [[Soho Square]].<ref>[[:File:Its Good News Week.jpg]], image courtesy of Wikipedia</ref><ref>[https://www.discogs.com/label/230005-Jonjo-Music-Ltd \"JonJo Music Ltd\"], Discogs. Retrieved 31 July 2016</ref><ref name=\"King11\">King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;11.</ref> Briefly banned by the BBC because of its lyrics about [[birth control]], the song made the top five in the UK and top 50 in America.<ref name=Eder>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jonathan-king-mn0000263019/biography |title=Jonathan King |author= Eder, Bruce |work=AllMusic |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first= David|last= Roberts|year= 2006|title= British Hit Singles & Albums|isbn= 978-1-904994-10-7|at= 249|title-link= British Hit Singles & Albums}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1965, King began contributing a column to ''[[Disc (magazine)|Disc and Music Echo]]'', a weekly magazine edited by [[Ray Coleman]]. King adopted a deliberately provocative style, promoting new acts but also publishing criticism of the music industry and particular artists.<ref name=King10>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;10.</ref> [[Michael Wale]] described him as \"the butterfly who stamped its foot\".<ref>Vale, Michael (1972). ''VoxPop'', Larousse Harrap Publishers, 78.</ref>\n\n===Discovery of Genesis===\nIn early 1967, King attended an old boys' reunion at Charterhouse. He said he went there to show off, \"oust[ing] [[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Baden Powell]] as their most famous Old Boy.\"<ref>Thompson, Dave (2004). ''Turn It on Again'', Hal Leonard Corporation, 11.</ref> When they heard he was going to be there, a school band recorded a demo tape for him, and a friend, John Alexander, left the [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] in King's car with a note, \"These are Charterhouse boys. Have a listen\".<ref>Rutherford, Mike (2014). ''The Living Years'', Constable, 45.</ref><ref name=\"Banks2007pp27\u201328\"/> Calling themselves [[Anon (band)|Anon]], the band consisted at that point of [[Peter Gabriel]], [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]], [[Anthony Phillips]], [[Chris Stewart (author)|Chris Stewart]] and [[Mike Rutherford]], then all aged 15 to 17.<ref name=Welch>Welch, Chris (1995). ''The Complete Guide to the Music of Genesis''. Omnibus Press, 1\u20133.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-29374866 |title=Jonathan King to appear in BBC Genesis documentary |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nKing liked several songs such as \"She is Beautiful\" (which became \"The Serpent\" on the band's first album) and, according to Philips, they got the deal with King on the basis of that song. King signed the band to JonJo Music and licensed the short-term rights to Decca Records. He paid them \u00a340 for four songs, and came up with their name, [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], to mark the start of his own career as a record producer.<ref name=\"Banks2007pp27\u201328\">Banks, Tony, et al. (2007). \"Charterhouse (1963\u20131968),\" in Philip Dodd (ed.), ''Genesis: Chapter and Verse'', St. Martin's Griffin, 27\u201328.</ref><ref name=Welch/> According to Phillips, King was \"hugely patient and indulgent\" with the band.<ref name=\"Banks2007pp27\u201328\"/> [[John Silver (musician)|John Silver]], drummer on the first album, wrote in 2007:\n\n<blockquote style=\"background:none; margin-right:5em; margin-left:0; border-left:solid 3px #ccc; padding:1.5em;\">\nWe would be pretending to rehearse or simply waiting around and somehow somebody would bring a message to the flat, \"Quick, get over to Jonathan King's flat, because [[Paul McCartney]]'s turning up.\" We would scurry over as quickly as possible because the art was to be there, looking casual, before the next famous person arrived, so that Jonathan King could say, \"Hey, these are my new prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.\" I trusted him as a god, because he knew these people. It wasn't celebrity like it is now. There were only a few famous people and he knew them. If Jonathan said jump or stand backwards or stand on your head, basically you did it. This was the nature of the relationship; he was completely omnipotent, in a decent way.<ref>Banks, et al. (2007), \"Christmas Cottage (1968\u20131970)\", 57.</ref></blockquote>\n\nKing produced their first three singles, including \"[[The Silent Sun]]\" (1968) and an album, ''[[From Genesis to Revelation]]'' (1969). Banks and Gabriel wrote \"The Silent Sun\" as a late-1960s [[Bee Gees]] \"pastiche\" to please King; [[Robin Gibb]]'s voice was apparently King's favourite at the time.<ref>Banks 2007, 29.</ref> The records made little impact; the album sold just 649 copies \"and we knew all of those people personally,\" wrote Banks. King slowly lost interest in the band. Their next demo was even less \"poppy\"; the more complicated the songs, the less King liked them.<ref name=Banks2007p52>Banks 2007, 52.</ref> Genesis left King in 1970 for [[Tony Stratton-Smith]]'s [[Charisma Records]], were joined by [[Phil Collins]] and [[Steve Hackett]]\u2014and, after another two unsuccessful albums, released ''[[Foxtrot (album)|Foxtrot]]'' (1972) to critical acclaim.<ref>White, Timothy (1986). \"Gabriel,\" ''Spin'' magazine (50\u201363),[https://books.google.com/books?id=772AV6upth4C&pg=PA54 54].</ref><ref name=EderGenesis>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/genesis-mn0000199995/biography |title=Genesis |author= Eder, Bruce |work=AllMusic |accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref> King retained the rights to the first album and re-released it several times under different titles.<ref name= Hombach>{{cite book |title=Phil Collins |last=Hombach |first=Jean-Pierre |year=2012 |isbn=978-1470134440 |at=17}}</ref> Rutherford said in 1985 that, \"for all his faults\", King had given the band an opportunity to record, which at that time was hard to come by.{{efn|[[Mike Rutherford]], 1985: \"Jonathan King, for all his faults&nbsp;\u2013 he has a funny reputation in England&nbsp;\u2013 did give us a fantastic opportunity. Because in those days, in England, you couldn't get in the studio. I mean, now a new group can very easily get a chance to go and record a single, just something, you know, to show there's something going for them. In those days, to get any sort of record contract, was really magical. And he gave us a chance to do a whole record. You've got a bunch of musicians who were really amateur, could barely play well, were barely a group, and were able to go in one summer holiday and make a record.\"<ref>{{cite AV media |people= Mike Rutherford interviewed by Dan Neer |year=1985 |title=Mike on Mike |url=http://www.discogs.com/Mike-The-Mechanics-Mike-On-Mike-Exclusive-Candid-Interview/release/2651552 |accessdate=22 January 2014 |format=Vinyl, 12\" Promo interview recording |publisher=Atlantic Recording Corporation|ref=Altlantic - PR820}}</ref>}}\n\n===Broadcasting, Decca Records===\n{{quote box\n|border=1px\n|title=External images\n|title_fnt=#555555\n|halign=left\n|quote=[http://media.gettyimages.com/photos/circa-1967-rock-guitarist-jimi-hendrix-centre-with-from-left-to-right-picture-id3304553 King with Jimi Hendrix]<br/>1 January 1967<br/>\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20161022214410/http://cache3.asset-cache.net/gc/546033355-english-singer-songwriter-jonathan-king-gettyimages.jpg?v=1&c=IWSAsset&k=2&d=X7WJLa88Cweo9HktRLaNXrm6/uLfAn6tHcLx/CqRX1%2BJAjdQwhEmXuNJgUUuJoOItvFtA5cHL1HUvOqohQ/PoA%3D%3D King at his graduation ceremony]<br/>23 June 1967<br/>\n[http://media.gettyimages.com/photos/23rd-february-jonathan-king-performs-on-top-of-the-pops-tv-show-23rd-picture-id111656793 King on ''Top of the Pops'']<br/>23 February 1972\n|qalign=center\n|fontsize=95%\n|bgcolor=#F9F9F9\n|bordercolor=#ccc\n|width=220px\n|align=right\n|salign=right\n|source=}}\n\nWhen King graduated from Cambridge in June 1967, the press covered his graduation ceremony: \"Jonathan King becomes M.A. (Cantab.)\".<ref>\"Jonathan King becomes M.A. (Cantab.)\", [[Londoner's Diary]], ''London Evening Standard'', 23 June 1967.</ref> Shortly afterwards Tony Firth, an [[Associated Television|ATV]] producer and Trinity graduate, asked King to present ''Good Evening'', a weekly television show that ran nationally on ATV at 6:30 pm on Saturdays from October 1967 to 1968.<ref>''Billboard'', 14 October 1967, [https://books.google.com/books?id=qiIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64 64]; for ATV, ''London Magazine'', 7, 1967, 59.</ref><ref>For 1968, Wale, Michael (1972).  ''Voxpop: Profiles of the Pop Process'', Larousse Harrap Publishers, 85.</ref> The following year he began broadcasting for [[BBC Radio 1]], including a \"blast off\" slot on the [[Stuart Henry (DJ)|Stuart Henry]] show.<ref name=King12>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;12.</ref>\n\nTired of living in the Dorset Street apartment, King bought a three-storey [[mews house]] near Porchester Terrace, Bayswater, in which he still lived as of 2019, for \u00a318,650.<ref>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;11; King, Jonathan (2014). ''70 FFFY'', London: Revvolution Publishing Ltd, [https://books.google.com/books?id=lbeWBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA158 158].</ref> Around this time, he was recruited by Sir [[Edward Lewis (Decca)|Edward Lewis]], the founder of Decca Records and another Trinity graduate, to be his unpaid (expenses only) personal assistant. King writes that Lewis recruited him twice for this position, once not long after graduation and again in the late 1970s.<ref name=\"King11\"/><ref>{{cite book |chapter = Jonathan King| title = The Da Capo Companion to 20th-century Popular Music |last=Hardy |first=Phil |author2=Laing, Dave |publisher = Da Capo Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-0306806407 |at=520}}</ref>\n\n===Early 1970s===\n{{further|1970s in music|Bubblegum pop}}\n\"[[It's Good News Week]]\" (1965) was the last big hit King had for four years. Then his cover of \"[[Let It Out (Let It All Hang Out)|Let It All Hang Out]]\" (1969) made the top 30 in January 1970, and he went on to become the top singles producer of 1971 and 1972,<ref name=Billboard27May1972>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-ycEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA51&lpg=RA1-PA51 \"UK Producer King Launches Own Label\"], ''Billboard'', 27 May 1972, 51.</ref> beginning with \"[[It's the Same Old Song]]\". Released by [[B&C Records]] in December 1970 under a pseudonym, the Weathermen, it moved into the charts a month later. Using pseudonyms meant more airtime: radio producers might play several songs by the same artist during a programme without realizing they had devoted so much airtime to one person.<ref name=King12/>\n\nKing's 1971 releases included a version of [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Mama, You Been on My Mind|Baby, You've Been On My Mind]]\", released as Nemo, which failed to chart; ''[[The Sun Has Got His Hat On]]'', also as Nemo; \"[[Sugar, Sugar]]\" as Sakkarin; \"[[Leap Up and Down (Wave Your Knickers in the Air)]]\" by St Cecelia (this one a real band, rather than a pseudonym), which went to number 12; and \"[[Lazy Bones]]\", \"[[Flirt]]\" and \"[[Hooked on a Feeling]]\" - all released under his own name.<ref name=King12/>\n\n[[Bell Records]] asked King to produce four songs for the [[Bay City Rollers]], including their first hit, \"[[Keep on Dancing (The Gentrys song)|Keep on Dancing]]\", on which King sang the 13 backing vocals himself. Released in May 1971, the single reached number nine.<ref>{{cite book |title=Bay City Babylon: The Unbelievable But True Story of the Bay City Rollers|last=Coy |first=Wayne|year= 2005|isbn= 978-1587364631|at=[https://books.google.com/books?id=X3841RiPCqUC&pg=PA23 23\u201327]}}</ref>\n\n\"Hooked on a Feeling\", a country song that King had turned into a pop hit, adding \"ooga chaka ooga ooga\" to the intro, was a Top Thirty hit. King's arrangement later gave Swedish group [[Blue Swede]] a US number one in April 1974.<ref>Bronson, Fred (2003). The Billboard Book of Number One Hits'', Billboard Books, [https://books.google.com/books?id=PgGqNrqfrsoC&pg=PT370 361].</ref> The arrangement featured in ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]'' (1992), at least one episode of ''[[Ally McBeal]]'', where it provided the music for the [[Dancing Baby]] (1998), and ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' (2014), although King writes that he made no money from the Blue Swede version.<ref>King, ''''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;12; King, ''FFFY'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=lbeWBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA13 13].</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Torstar |first=Staff |url= http://metronews.ca/scene/1133744/heard-in-guar...ats-with-ooga-chaka |title=Heard in Guardians of the Galaxy: What's with 'ooga chaka'? |work=Metronews |date=22 August 2014}}</ref> Years later the track still garners coverage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8505891/hooked-on-a-feeling-sweden|title=Hooked on the Ooga Chagga: Sweden's First Hot 100 No. 1 Was Unleashed 45 Years Ago Today|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nAnother top three 1971 hit was \"[[Johnny Reggae]]\", a [[ska]] pop song about a [[skinhead]], written by King after he was introduced to a Johnny Reggae at the [[Walton Hop]] disco in Surrey.<ref name=King12/> It was sung by King and middle-aged session singers pretending to be teenagers, credited to [[The Piglets]] and released by Bell.<ref name=King12/><ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/bll1180 \"Record Details\"], www.45cat.com.</ref> John Stratton writes that \"Johnny Reggae\" was the \"first British hit with a ska beat to have been written by a white Englishman&nbsp;... and performed by white English singers and musicians.\"<ref>Stratton, John (2016). \"The Travels of Johnny Reggae: From Jonathan King to Prince Far I</ref><ref>From Skinhead to Rasta,\" ''When Music Migrates: Crossing British and European Racial Faultlines, 1945\u20132010''. Routledge (59\u201379), 59\u201360.</ref> While, according to [[Lloyd Bradley]], the BBC was reluctant to play [[reggae]] by black Jamaican artists, \"Johnny Reggae\", which Bradley described as \"lamentable [and] audibly jarring\", reached number three in the UK in November 1971 (when [[Slade]]'s \"[[Coz I Luv You]]\" was number one) and stayed in the top 50 for 12 weeks.<ref>Stratton 2016, 59\u201360; Bradley, Lloyd (2001). ''Bass Culture: When Reggae Was King''. Penguin, 256 (also published as ''This is Reggae Music'').</ref>{{efn|A Jamaican version of \"Johnny Reggae\", \"Heavy Reggae (Johnny Reggae)\", was released in 1974 by the Roosevelt Singers.<ref>Stratton 2016, 60.</ref>}}\n\nIt has been reported that, under various different names and in assorted formats, he sold around 40 million records.<ref name=\"ronson_fall\" />\n\n===UK Records===\n[[File:10CC - TopPop 1974 2.png|thumb|[[10cc]] in 1974. ''Clockwise from left'': [[Eric Stewart]], [[Kevin Godley]], [[Graham Gouldman]] and [[Lol Creme]]]]\nIn 1972 King set up a record label, [[UK Records]], distributed by Decca and later [[Polygram]] in the UK and [[London Records]] in the US. [[Chris Denning]] left Bell to run the UK office and Fred Ruppert, formerly of [[Elektra Records]], the US office.<ref name=Eder/><ref name=BillboardSept1972/><ref name=Billboard27May1972/> Don Wardell <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1073modfm.com/shows/don-wardell/|title=Don Wardell}}</ref> then took over the US office, Denning left and Wardell moved back to run the UK company. King's brother Andy was hired in 1974 as the promotion manager.<ref>\"International Turntable,\" ''Billboard'', 22 June 1974, [https://books.google.com/books?id=YgkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52 52].</ref> Clive Selwood,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.7tt77.co.uk/UK.html|title=UK|website=www.7tt77.co.uk}}</ref> who had helmed [[John Peel]]'s label [[Dandelion]], then took over as manager.<ref>{{Cite book|title=All the Moves (but None of the Licks): Secrets of the Record Business: Amazon.co.uk: Clive Selwood: 9780720611533: Books |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date= |id= {{ASIN|0720611539|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\nThe label's first hit was \"[[Seaside Shuffle]]\" by [[Terry Dactyl and the Dinosaurs]], followed by King's \"[[Loop di Love]]\", which reached number four, released under the pseudonym Shag.<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/uk7 \"Shag\"], www.45cat.com. Retrieved 31 July 2016.</ref> Other signings included [[Ricky Wilde]], then 11 years old and promoted to fill the gap later taken by [[Donny Osmond]], a potential [[David Cassidy]], [[Simon Fisher Turner|Simon Turner]],<ref>Partridge, Rob (23 December 1972). \"New Pop Audience Emerging in U.K.\", ''Billboard'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=Rw8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10 10].</ref> [[Roy C]], [[the First Class]] and [[Lobo (musician)|Lobo]]. The label also released King's cover of \"[[(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction]]\" (1974) under the name Bubblerock, described as a \"[[Grateful Dead]]\"-style country version\", which met the approval of [[Mick Jagger]].<ref name=Eder/><ref name= southall>{{cite book |title=The A-Z of record labels |last=Southall |first=Brian |year=2003 |isbn=978-1860744921 |at=[https://archive.org/details/azofrecordlabels0000sout/page/276 276] |url=https://archive.org/details/azofrecordlabels0000sout/page/276 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66cTHKWtfAE \"Jonathan King&nbsp;\u2013 Satisfaction\"], YouTube.</ref>\n\nIn June 1973, after seeing ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'' on its second night, King invested a 20% stake in it, making him one of its two original backers, along with [[Michael White (producer)|Michael White]], and produced and released ''The Rocky Horror Show Original London Cast''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockymusic.org/recording/london-73.php|title=The Rocky Horror Show Original London Cast|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=Chalmers22April2012>{{cite news |title= Jonathan King: 'The only apology I have is to say that I was good at seduction' |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jonathan-king-the-only-apology-i-have-is-to-say-that-i-was-good-at-seduction-7658249.html |newspaper=The Independent on Sunday |date=22 April 2012 |author=Chalmers, Robert}}</ref><ref>Thompson, Dave (2016). ''The Rocky Horror Picture Show FAQ'', Hal Leonard Corporation.</ref>\n\nThe label's most significant signing was [[10cc]]. [[Eric Stewart]], one of the band members, had known King since 1965, when Stewart was with [[The Mindbenders]] and King had wanted to manage them. The band had planned to release \"[[Donna (10cc song)|Donna]]\" as a B side, but decided it could be a hit: \"We only knew of one person who was mad enough to release it,\" Stewart said, \"and that was Jonathan King.\"<ref>Tremlett, George (1976). ''The 10cc Story'' Futura.</ref><ref>Thompson, Dave (2012). ''The Cost of Living in Dreams: The 10cc Story'', CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, p. 61\u201362.</ref> King gave the band its name and released two of the group's albums (''[[10cc (album)|10cc]]'' and ''[[Sheet Music (album)|Sheet Music]]'') and eight singles. \"Donna\" (1972) and \"[[Rubber Bullets]]\" (1973), reached number two and one respectively, followed by \"[[The Dean and I]]\" (1973) and \"[[The Wall Street Shuffle]]\" (1974).<ref>Davis, Sharon (2012). ''Every Chart Topper Tells a Story: The Seventies'', Random House.</ref>  The band only dented the American market, with \"Rubber Bullets\" making 73 on the [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/431837/10cc/chart |title=10cc - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> 10cc left UK Records in 1975 for [[Mercury Records]], after which they achieved success in America, particularly with \"[[I'm Not in Love]]\" (1975).<ref name=Ankeny>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/10cc-mn0000502163/biography |title=10cc |author=Ankeny, Jason |work=AllMusic |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Move to New York===\n[[File:Jonathan King 1982.jpeg|thumb|left|King in 1982]]\nIn April 1978 King stood for [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] as an independent in the [[1978 Epsom and Ewell by-election|Epsom and Ewell by-election]], calling himself the Royalist party. He gained 2,350 votes.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120314034520/http://by-elections.co.uk/78.html \"1978 By Election Results\"], by-elections.co.uk</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Relentless ego of self-styled man |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/relentless-ego-of-selfstyled-man-6335578.html |newspaper=London Evening Standard |author= Arkell, Harriet |date=21 November 2001}}</ref> A year later he decided to leave the music industry and closed UK Records.<ref name=southall/> He wrote to the charts committee of the [[British Phonographic Industry]] in August 1979 alleging that the lower levels of the charts reflected \"clever promotion and marketing rather than good records\", and suggesting that only information about the top 30 should be made available. The idea was that this would force programmers to base their airplay decisions on something other than the lower charts.<ref>\"King Advocates Chart Cuts,\" ''Billboard'', 25 August 1979, [https://books.google.com/books?id=FiUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT65 68].</ref>\n\nThe UK Records New York office on [[57th Street (Manhattan)|57th Street]] was turned into an apartment, and King set about building a new career in writing and broadcasting. He was given a weekly five-minute slot on BBC Radio 1 called \"A King in New York\", a \"Postcard from America\" slot in Radio 4, and he reported for Radio 1 on the 1980 presidential election.<ref>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;15.</ref> In December 1980, watching television in bed, he heard there had been a shooting outside the [[The Dakota|Dakota Apartments]]. He called and woke up BBC producer [[Tom Brook]], who was living in New York; Brook became the first to announce to the UK that [[John Lennon]] had died.<ref>Brooks, Tom (8 December 2010). [https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-11926898 \"Lennon's death: I was there\"], BBC News.</ref>\n\nThroughout 1980 and 1981 King presented a radio talk show on New York's [[WMCA (AM)|WMCA]] from 10\u201312 weekday mornings, and regularly reported from the United States on ''[[Top of the Pops]]''. He devised and hosted a spinoff series, ''[[Entertainment USA]]'', broadcast on [[BBC Two|BBC 2]], which was nominated for a [[BAFTA]] in 1987.<ref>[http://awards.bafta.org/award/1987/television/light-entertainment-programme \"Television. Light Entertainment Programme in 1987\"], BAFTA and peaked with 9.7 million viewers.</ref> He also created and produced ''[[No Limits (BBC TV series)|No Limits]]'', a youth programme.<ref>Yockel, Michael (30 July 2002). [http://www.nypress.com/jonathan-king-queen-of-pop/ \"Jonathan King, Queen of Pop\"], ''New York Press''.</ref>\n\nHis first novel, ''Bible Two'', was published in 1982. It tells the story of a window dresser in \"Selfishes\" who inherits his family's millions. He was also hired by [[Kelvin MacKenzie]], editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', to write a weekly column, \"Bizarre USA\", which began in February 1985 and continued for eight years.<ref name=King16>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;16.</ref> He continued with several music projects, including with the hard-rock [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] [[Gogmagog (band)|Gogmagog]], which released an [[Extended play|EP]], ''I Will Be There'' (1985).<ref>Munro, Eden (25 March 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20111005110337/http://vueweekly.com/music/story/old_sounds_gogmagog/ \"Gogmagog\"], ''Vue''.</ref><ref name= GuardianNov2000>{{cite news |title=Who is Jonathan King? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/nov/24/6 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=24 November 2000}}</ref>\n\n===Brit Awards, Eurovision Song Contest===\nIn 1987 King hosted the [[Brit Awards]] for the BBC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1987|title= Brit Awards 1987|publisher=Brits.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> and from 1990 to 1992 was the event's producer. He resigned just after the 1992 show because he and the [[British Phonographic Industry]], which runs the awards, disagreed about the show's format.<ref name=BBC24Nov2000>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1038651.stm \"The music industry's outsider\"], BBC News, 24 November 2000. Note: the BBC says that King resigned from the Brit Awards in 1991, but this appears to be an error.</ref><ref>Lister, David (17 January 1997). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/jonathan-king-calls-for-boycott-of-brit-awards-1283670.html \"Jonathan King calls for boycott of Brit awards\"], ''The Independent''</ref><ref>King, ''65 My Life So Far'', ch.&nbsp;17.</ref> The following year he founded ''[[The Tip Sheet]]'' (1993\u20132002), an influential weekly trade magazine promoting new acts.<ref>{{cite news |title=King's Tip Sheet to carry on |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/1668370.stm |publisher =BBC News |date=21 November 2001}}</ref>\n\nKing's media work included finding and producing the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] entrant for the BBC from 1995. He selected several songs for them.<ref name=BBC24Nov2000/> [[Love City Groove]]'s song, \"[[Love City Groove (song)|Love City Groove]]\", came tenth in 1995. [[Gina G]]'s \"[[Ooh Aah... Just a Little Bit]]\" came eighth the following year, and was number one in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/year/participant-profile/?song=20874|title=About Gina G|work=eurovision.tv|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> \"[[Love Shine A Light]]\" by [[Katrina and the Waves]] came first in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why Eurovision needs to be saved from the BBC|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/features/8910331/my-vision-for-eurovision/ |work=[[The Spectator]] |date=18 May 2013 }}</ref> His entry for 1998, when the UK hosted the event in [[Birmingham]], was by [[Imaani]] and came second.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tristram Fane |last=Saunders |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/eurovision-every-single-uk-entry-ranked-rated-worst-best/ |title=Eurovision: every single UK entry ranked, from worst to best |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2 May 2018 |location= London}}</ref> His writing continued. His second novel, ''The Booker Prize Winner'', was published that year. He was  involved in finding and promoting the [[Chumbawamba]] hit \"[[Tubthumping]]\" (1997), which made number two,<ref>King, ''70 FFFY'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=lbeWBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA86 86\u201389].</ref> and the [[Baha Men]]'s number one hit, \"[[Who Let the Dogs Out?]]\" (2000) which he first released under the name Fat Jakk and his Pack of Pets.<ref name=\"Rushfield2011\">{{cite book|author=Richard Rushfield|title=American Idol: The Untold Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eolrAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT22|date=18 January 2011|publisher=Hachette Books|isbn=978-1-4013-9652-7|pages=22\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/who-let-dogs-out-documentary-director-interview-1203159482/|title=\u2018Who Let the Dogs Out?\u2019 Doc Offers Fascinating Look at the Origin of the Baha Men Hit|first1=Charlie|last1=Amter|first2=Charlie|last2=Amter|date=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1997 King received a Music Industry Trusts Award at a dinner held in his honour at the [[Grosvenor House Hotel]] in London. A video tribute to him featured [[Guy Mitchell]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[The Moody Blues]] and [[Hanson (UK band)|Hanson]].<ref name=MITAward>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150316061237/http://www.mitsaward.co.uk/previous-recipients.html \"Previous award recipients\"], Music Industry Trusts Award, 16 March 2015</ref><ref>\"Newsline,\" ''Billboard'', 15 November 1997, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6QkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA50 50]</ref><ref>[http://marshall.photoshelter.com/gallery/MIT-Award-1997-Jonathan-King/G0000de0H3TFOhOU/C0000D542EBjhSiU \"MIT Award 1997 Jonathan King\"], JME Photo Library. Retrieved 1 August 2016.</ref><!--Can't find this in the Independent's archive; needs verifiable source from 1997: with a message of support from the then-prime minister [[Tony Blair]] for his \"important contribution to one of this country's great success stories.\"<ref>{{cite news |author= Burrell, Ian |date=24 October 1997 |work= The Independent |title= Blair goes loop di love over King |quote=}}</ref>--><ref>McGee, Alan (23 January 2007). [https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2007/jan/23/shouldthebpidethronejonath \"Should the BPI dethrone Jonathan King?\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref> The following year he devised ''[[The Record of the Year]]'', produced by his ''Tip Sheet'' and [[London Weekend Television]], a show in which the public voted for the year's best single.<ref>Young, Graham (19 December 1998). [https://web.archive.org/web/20160911025948/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-61443708.html \"I'm the Greatest!; (Says Jonathan King)\"], ''Birmingham Evening Mail''.</ref><ref>Sexton, Paul (25 December 1999). \"U.K. TV Awards Show Boosts Sales,\" ''Billboard'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA5 5], [https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA81 81].</ref> In 2000 [[Nigel Lythgoe]], executive producer of the new ''[[Popstars (UK TV series)|Popstars]]'' talent show, considered hiring King as anchor of its judging panel, but he turned it down. Lythgoe took the position himself.<ref>Nolan, David (2010). ''Simon Cowell&nbsp;\u2013 The Man Who Changed the World'', John Blake Publishing Ltd., 61.</ref><ref>Rushfield, Richard (2011). ''American Idol: The Untold Story'', Hachette Books, 15\u201316; Rushfield, Richard (15 January 2011)</ref><ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/battle-american-idol-66743 \"The Battle for 'American Idol'\"], ''Newsweek''</ref>\n\nKing reportedly turned down the chance to manage [[the KLF]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=The Justified Ancients of Mu Mu|title=2023|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-33808-5|year=2017}}</ref>\n\n===2001 trials and imprisonment for noncing===\nIn September 2001 King was convicted, after a two-week trial at the [[Old Bailey]], on four counts of [[indecent assault]], one of [[buggery]] and one of attempted buggery, committed between 1983 and 1987 against five boys aged 14 and 15. In a second trial he was found not guilty after an alleged victim (someone King denied having ever met) acknowledged that he could have been 16 or older at the time. Three further trials that had been scheduled were ordered abandoned.{{efn|At the time of the alleged offences, the applicable legislation was the [[Sexual Offences Act 1967]]. This decriminalized private consensual homosexual acts between parties aged 21 and over. If the sex was consensual and the alleged victim was 16 or over, the statute of limitations was 12 months.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1967/60/pdfs/ukpga_19670060_en.pdf ''Sexual Offences Act 1967''], legislation.gov.uk.</ref>}}<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/nov/21/childprotection.society \"Jonathan King jailed for child sex abuse\"]. ''The Guardian''. London. 21 November 2001.</ref><ref name=\"ronson_fall\">Ronson, Jon (1 December 2001). [https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2001/dec/01/weekend.jonronson \"The fall of a pop impresario\"]. ''The Guardian''</ref><ref>Ronson, Jon (2006). \"The Fall of a Pop Impresario,\" ''Out of the Ordinary True Tales of Everyday Craziness'', Picador, 192\u2013240.</ref> King continued to maintain his innocence throughout, protesting, among other things, that the lack of a [[Limitation periods in the UK|statute of limitations]] in the UK for sex offences meant he had been unable to defend himself adequately because of the many years that had passed.<ref name=Clough/>\n\nThe [[National Criminal Intelligence Service]] had begun investigating King for [[Child sexual abuse in the United Kingdom|child sexual abuse]] in 2000, when a man told them he had been assaulted by King and others 30 years earlier.<ref name=Hall22Nov2001>Hall, Sarah (22 November 2001). [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/nov/22/childprotection.society1 \"Victim's angry email led to downfall\"]. ''The Guardian''. London.</ref> The man had originally approached publicist [[Max Clifford]], himself later jailed in 2014 for sexual assault, about other men; Clifford told him that he needed to include a celebrity in his allegations and that he should go to the police.<ref>Norman, Matthew (4 May 2014). [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/max-clifford-played-a-crucial-role-in-the-conviction-of-jonathan-king-now-the-roles-have-been-9322804.html \"Max Clifford played a crucial role in the conviction of Jonathan King. Now the roles have been reversed\"], ''The Independent''. London.</ref> King was arrested in November that year and [[Bail#England and Wales|bailed]] on \u00a3150,000, \u00a350,000 of which was put up by [[Simon Cowell]].<ref name=Walker27Nov2011>Walker, Tim (27 November 2011). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jonathan-king-my-books-an-online-hit-millions-click-on-my-videos-how-about-lifting-the-media-ban-on-6268884.html \"Jonathan King: 'My book's an online hit, millions click on my videos. How about lifting the media ban on me?'\"], ''The Independent''.</ref> He was arrested again in January 2001 on further allegations.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/1134023.stm \"Second arrest for Jonathan King\"], ''The Guardian'', 24 January 2001.</ref><ref name=BBC25Jan2001>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/1136874.stm \"King faces fresh charges\"]. ''BBC News''. 25 January 2001.</ref> Twenty-seven men told police that King had sexually assaulted them during the period 1969\u20131989.<ref name=ONeill22November2001>{{cite news |title=The shameful private life hidden behind flamboyant self-publicity |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1363095/The-shameful-private-life-hidden-behind-flamboyant-self-publicity.html |author= O'Neill, Sean |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=22 November 2001}}</ref> Police found pictures of teenagers in a search of King's home.<ref name=ONeill22November2001/> King admitted having approached thousands of people with questionnaires about youth interests, doing market research. The questionnaires asked recipients to list topics according to importance including music, sport, friends and family; the prosecution claimed that boys who listed sex high in their list of priorities were then targeted by King.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/1666935.stm \"King's path to shame\"]. ''BBC News''. 21 November 2001.</ref>\n\nAfter the second trial at the Old Bailey on 21 November 2001, Judge David Paget QC sentenced King to 7 years in prison using the first trial verdict as a sample for \"all previous sexual behaviour\". In addition, King was placed on the [[Violent and Sex Offender Register|Sex Offenders Register]], prohibited from working with children, and ordered to pay \u00a314,000 costs.<ref name=Clough>Clough, Sue; O'Neill, Sean (22 November 2001). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1363094/Pop-veteran-Jonathan-King-given-seven-years-for-abusing-schoolboys.html \"Pop veteran Jonathan King given seven years for abusing schoolboys\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. London.</ref>{{efn|King served his sentence in [[HM Prison Belmarsh|Belmarsh]], [[HM Prison Elmley|Elmley]] and [[HM Prison Maidstone|Maidstone]] prisons.<ref>King, Jonathan (13 June 2004). [https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2004/jun/13/foodanddrink.features4 \"What's on your prison tray?&nbsp;\u2013 Jonathan King\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref>}} In 2003 the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] rejected his application to appeal both the conviction and the sentence; he had argued that the conviction was unsafe and the sentence, with guidelines of two years, had been \"manifestly too severe\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2691803.stm |date=24 January 2003 |title=King loses appeal bid |work=BBC News}}</ref> He appealed twice unsuccessfully to the [[Criminal Cases Review Commission]],<ref>Tryhorn, Chris (15 April 2003). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/apr/15/broadcasting.radio \"King makes fresh appeal bid\"], ''The Guardian''</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/4660558.stm |title=King abuse case 'to be reviewed |work=BBC News |date=29 January 2006}}</ref> and was released on [[parole]] in March 2005.<ref name=Milmo29March2005>Milmo, Cahal (29 March 2005). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/jonathan-king-i-have-had-a-brilliant-time-7907527.html \"Jonathan King: 'I have had a brilliant time'\"], ''The Independent''.</ref>\n\nKing has complained about his media coverage since his 2001 conviction. In 2005 he went to the [[Press Complaints Commission]] about an article in the ''[[News of the World]]'' that said he had gone to a park to \"ogle\" boys. In fact he had gone there at the request of a documentary maker. The complaint was not upheld, but [[Roy Greenslade]] argued that King had a good case.<ref>Greenslade, Roy (4 July 2005). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/jul/04/newsoftheworld.mondaymediasection \"King had cause for complaint\"], ''The Guardian''.</ref> In October 2011 then BBC [[Director-General of the BBC|Director-General]] [[Mark Thompson (television executive)|Mark Thompson]] apologised to King for the removal of King's performance of \"[[It Only Takes a Minute]]\" from a repeat, on [[BBC Four]], of a 1976 episode of ''[[Top of the Pops]]''. King described the cut as a \"Stalinist revision approach to history\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC apology to Jonathan King after he is cut from repeat |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8835884/BBC-apology-to-Jonathan-King-after-he-is-cut-from-repeat.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=19 October 2011}}</ref> When asked by a newspaper in 2012 if he believed he had anything to apologise for, to anybody from his past, King replied, \"The only apology I have is to say that I was good at seduction. I was good at making myself seem attractive when I wasn't very attractive at all\".<ref name=apology>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jonathan-king-the-only-apology-i-have-is-to-say-that-i-was-good-at-seduction-7658249.html|title=Jonathan King: 'The only apology I have is to say that I was good at seduction'|work=[[The Independent]]|date=21 April 2012|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> He appeared in front of the [[Leveson Inquiry]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/leveson-inquiry/9039169/Leveson-inquiry-Jonathan-King-claims-his-was-miscarriage-of-justice-victim.html | title=Leveson inquiry: Jonathan King claims his was miscarriage of justice victim| date=2012-01-25| last1=Rayner| first1=Gordon}}</ref>\n\n===After prison===\nJournalist Robert Chalmers wrote that King's creative output after he left prison \"resembled a primal scream of rage\".<ref name=Chalmers22April2012/><ref name=walker/> Two novels appeared: ''Beware the Monkey Man'' (2010), under the pen name Rex Kenny, and ''Death Flies, Missing Girls and Brigitte Bardot'' (2013), under his real name, Kenneth George King. He also published a diary, ''Three Months'' (2012), and two volumes of his autobiography, ''Jonathan King 65: My Life So Far'' (2009) and ''70 FFFY'' (2014).\n\nKing maintained an interest in prison issues and writes a column for ''[[Inside Time]]'', the national newspaper for prisoners.<ref>[http://www.insidetime.org/?s=%22Jonathan+King%22 \"Jonathan King\"], ''Inside Time''.</ref>\n\nHe released ''Earth to King'' in 2008. One of the new songs on the album, \"The True Story of Harold Shipman\" was about the serial killer Dr. [[Harold Shipman]], in which King suggested that Shipman may have been a victim of the media.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/6896298.stm \"Families' anger over Shipman song\"], BBC News, 12 July 2007.</ref> He also produced three films. ''Vile Pervert: The Musical'' (2008), available for free download, is a 96-minute film in which King plays all 21 parts and presents his version of events surrounding his prosecution.  He portrays his viewpoint of the events responsible for his troubles.<ref name=vp>{{cite news |title= Jonathan King makes Vile Pervert: The Musical |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1958447/Jonathan-King-makes-Vile-Pervert-The-Musical.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 May 2008 |first=Matthew |last=Moore}}</ref> In one scene King, dressed as [[Oscar Wilde]], sings that there is \"nothing wrong with buggering boys\".<ref name=vp/> [[Rod Liddle]] called it \"a fantastically berserk, bravado performance\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Liddle |first=Rod |title=The King strikes back |url= http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/rod-liddle/2011/10/the-king-strikes-back/ |work=The Spectator|date=22 October 2011}}</ref> ''Me Me Me'' (2011) was described at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] as \"a re-telling of ''Romeo and Juliet''\".<ref>Sharp, Rob (12 May 2011). [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/cannes-diary-from-disgraced-dlisters-to-exdrug-dealing-singers-festival-embraces-them-all-2282720.html \"Cannes Diary: From disgraced D-listers to ex-drug dealing singers, festival embraces them all\"], ''The Independent''.</ref> ''The Pink Marble Egg'' (2013) is a spy story; for publicity King drove down the [[Promenade de la Croisette]] in Cannes with a pink [[papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]] egg on top of his Rolls Royce during the [[Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Wells, Dominic |url= http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/469154/20130520/cannes-film-festival-marilyn-monroe-lesbian-weddings.htm |title=Cannes Film Festival 2013: Marilyn Monroe, Lesbian Weddings, Nuns of the Future and Occupy Movement |work= International Business Times UK |date=20 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2018 trial===\nIn August 2015, King wrote an article for ''[[The Spectator]]'' magazine concerning [[Sir Edward Heath]], the subject of the now-discredited [[Operation Midland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/08/edward-heath-wasnt-gay-trust-me-i-tried-and-failed-to-seduce-him/|title=Why I don\u2019t believe that Ted Heath was gay|date=7 August 2015|website=Blogs.spectator.co.uk}}</ref> In September 2015, King was arrested as part of [[Operation Yewtree#Operation Ravine|Operation Ravine]], a further investigation into claims of sexual abuse at the [[Walton Hop]] disco in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34205654|title=Jonathan King arrested in child sex offences probe |work= BBC News |date=10 September 2015}}</ref> He was later released on bail.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-34214022 \"Jonathan King freed on bail over sex offence claims\"]. ''BBC News''. 10 September 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-surrey-36472233 \"Ex-DJ Denning charged with child sex offences\"]. ''BBC News''. 7 June 2016.</ref>  On 25 May 2017, he was charged by [[Surrey Police]] with 18 sexual offences, relating to nine boys aged between 14 and 16, allegedly carried out between 1970 and 1986.  He was released on bail and appeared at [[Westminster Magistrates' Court]] on 26 June,<ref name=bbc40044654>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-40044654|title=Music mogul Jonathan King charged with historical sex offences |publisher= BBC News |date=25 May 2017}}</ref> where he was released on conditional bail to appear at [[Southwark Crown Court]] on 31 July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-40405058|title=Music mogul Jonathan King in court over sex crimes|work=[[BBC News]]|date=26 June 2017|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/26/ex-dj-jonathan-king-arrives-court-charged-historical-sex-attacks/ |title=Ex-DJ Jonathan King gives thumbs up after appearing in court on child sex charges |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=26 June 2017 |accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref> His trial began on 11 June 2018, and on 27 June the jury was discharged for legal reasons.<ref>{{cite news |first=Catherine |last=Wylie |url= http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/ex-music-mogul-jonathan-king-13411841 |title=Ex music mogul Jonathan King appears in court over Walton Hop child sex abuse claims |work=GetSurrey|date=31 July 2017|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-44634770|title=Music mogul Jonathan King sex trial jurors discharged |work=BBC News|date=27 June 2018|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2018, King received an apology for the collapse of the trial, with Judge Deborah Taylor saying that Surrey Police had made \"numerous, repeated and compounded\" errors during the investigation, describing the situation as a \"debacle\". In her ruling she said \"I have concluded that this is a case where even if it were possible to have a fair trial, it is in the rare category where the balance, taking account of the history, the failures and misleading of the Court, is in favour of a stay on the basis that following what has occurred, continuation would undermine public confidence in the administration of justice\".<ref>[http://www.chrissaltrese.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/King-Further-abuse-ruling-redactedapproved.pdf Further ruling on application for a stay] ''R v Kenneth King''. Retrieved 9 September 2018.</ref>  Taylor said that the case against King had been motivated by \"concerns about reputational damage to Surrey Police\" following the allegations of sexual abuse against [[Jimmy Savile]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher|last=McKeon|url= https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/surrey-police-failures-jonathan-king-15070657|title=Surrey Police failures in Jonathan King child sex abuse investigation 'undermined criminal justice system'|work=SurreyLive |date=30 August 2018|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> Surrey Police \"wholeheartedly apologised\" to King, saying \"We deeply regret that despite these efforts we did not meet the required standards to ensure a fair trial.\"<ref name = \"2018_trial\">{{cite news |first=Victoria|last=Ward|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/08/06/surrey-police-apologise-judgment-reveals-disclosure-failings/|title=Surrey Police apologise after judgment reveals disclosure failings in Jonathan King sex abuse case |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=6 August 2018|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> King refused to accept the apology, and criticised Surrey Police for \"deep, institutional faults\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-45134168|title=Music mogul Jonathan King slams police apology|work=[[BBC News]]|date=10 August 2018|accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref><ref name= \"finkelstein\" /> He urged both the [[Surrey Police#Chief Constables|Chief Constable]] and the [[Surrey Police and Crime Commissioner|Police and Crime Commissioner]] to go.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.farnhamherald.com/article.cfm?id=134078&headline=Former+DJ+King+calls+for+Munro+to+step+down&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2019|title=Former DJ King calls for Munro to step down|newspaper=Farnham Herald}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/chief-constable-nick-ephgrave-leave-15549383|title=Chief Constable Nick Ephgrave to leave Surrey Police for Met|first=Christopher|last=McKeon|date=13 December 2018|website=getsurrey}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.farnhamherald.com/article.cfm?id=135316&headline=Munro+loses+crime+commissioner+vote&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2019|title=Munro loses crime commissioner vote|newspaper=Farnham Herald}}</ref> In August 2019 Chief Constable Stephens, who had replaced Ephgrave, announced that, in the year since King's acquittal, the Surrey Police success rate for convictions in sex abuse cases had dropped from 20% to \"under 4%\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-surrey-49350013|title=Backlog of child sex offences 'significant'|date=14 August 2019|website=Bbc.com}}</ref> On 22 November 2019, an independent review into the police investigation leading to the trial was published. It was critical of the handling of disclosure of documents to King's defence prior to the trial, and questioned whether some of the  staff involved had been qualified or experienced enough to handle the case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-50518077|title=Jonathan King child abuse trial: Surrey Police criticised over collapse|work=[[BBC News]]|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.surrey.police.uk/SysSiteAssets/media/downloads/surrey/news/operation-ravine-peer-review-report-november-2019.pdf Operation Ravine Peer Review Report] Surrey Police, 22 November 2019.</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n===Singles discography===\n====As performer====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:left; float:center; margin-left:10px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=5 | As performer or producer/performer\n|-\n!   || Single<br/><small>([[A-side and B-side|A and B side]])</small>|| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref>{{cite book| first= Graham| last= Betts| year=2004| title= Complete UK Hit Singles 1952-2004|publisher= Collins| location= London| isbn= 978-0-00-717931-2| at=429}}</ref><ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/11916/jonathan-king/ \"Jonathan King\"], officialcharts.com.</ref>|| Credited to|| Label\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1965 || \"Gotta Tell\" / \"When I Come to You\" || || Terry Ward with the Bumblies {{efn|Both sides of the Terry Ward record were written and produced by King.}} ||  [[Fontana Records|Fontana]]<ref name=GottaTell>[http://www.45cat.com/record/tf558 \"Record Details\"], 45cat.com.</ref>\n|-\n|| \"[[Everyone's Gone to the Moon]]\" / \"Summer's Coming\" ||4||Jonathan King  || [[Decca Records|Decca]]<ref name=JK45ca